\begin_layout Subsection
Equilibrium Properties
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
An equilibrium might (or might not) have the following desirable properties:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Existence
\series default
 - does it exist at all (is it a steady state) ?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Uniqueness
\series default
 - there might be several equilibria
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Dynamic stability
\series default
 - a point is dynamically stable, when a small change in the input values
 does not result in a big change in the output result.
 In order words - this is a measure of whether dynamic forces will push
 the state back towards the equilibrium, far away from it or neither
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Robustness
\series default
 - does a small error introduce a dramatic change?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A 
\series bold
partial equilibrium
\series default
 (single market) has all these properties: given demand and supply curves,
 they 
\series bold
intercept
\series default
 in a 
\series bold
single
\series default
 point.
 
\series bold
Market forces
\series default
 push the state back towards it (thus it had dynamic stability), and a small
 error in initial condition doesn't cause big error in the result (robustness).
\end_layout

