\begin_layout Section
Preference over consumption periods
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We didn't deal yet with intertemporal issues: saving for future and uncertainity.
 For simplicity 2 periods will be assumed.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The idea is that given known incomes in both periods, consumption bundles
 can be calculated by using the consumer preferences.
 The classical model of discounting the future:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
U(c_{0},c_{1},c_{2},\ldots)=u(c_{0})+\delta u(c_{1})+\delta^{2}u(c_{2})+\cdots
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $0<\delta<1$
\end_inset

 is the 
\series bold
discount factor
\series default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Without financial market, given an income 
\begin_inset Formula $(y_{0},y_{1})$
\end_inset

 it is the only possible consumption set.
 But if saving/borrowing are possible, every 
\begin_inset Formula $\$1$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

 today can be converted to 
\begin_inset Formula $\$(1+r)$
\end_inset

 tomorrow, and vice-versa.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Therefore the budget set can be represented on a graph, where consumption
 in the first period and the second one correspond to the 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 axes.
 A consumer can spend all the income today (
\begin_inset Formula $y_{o}+\frac{y_{1}}{1+r}$
\end_inset

) or in the next period (
\begin_inset Formula $(1+r)y_{0}+y_{1}$
\end_inset

) or any combination inbetween.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The optimal choice (assuming Cobb-Douglas preference pattern) is given by:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
U(c_{0},c_{1})=log(c_{0})+\delta log(c_{1})
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{U_{0}}{U_{1}}=\frac{c_{1}}{\delta c_{0}}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Given an initial endowment (budget schedule) a consumer might make a decision
 to 
\series bold
save
\series default
 or to 
\series bold
borrow
\series default
 - in order to reach the equilibrium point.
 The decision depends on the given endowment, time preferences and the interest
 rate.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The effect of 
\series bold
endowment
\series default
: depending on the initial position on the budget line, a shift on the line
 may be needed (by saving or borrowing).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The effect of 
\series bold
time preferences
\series default
 influences on the shape of the indifference curve (
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{y_{1}}{\delta y_{0}}$
\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Effect of the
\series bold
 interest rate
\series default
 defines the slope of the budget line.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A special (yet important) case occurs when an income is fixed (
\begin_inset Formula $y_{0}=y_{1}$
\end_inset

), then 
\begin_inset Formula $1+r$
\end_inset

 is comparable to 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{1}{\delta}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Recalling the CD utility function, the consumptions can be calculated using
 the budget consraint:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(1+r)c_{0}+c_{1}=(2+r)y
\]

\end_inset

and given 
\begin_inset Formula $y=y_{0}=y_{1}$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
c_{0}^{*}=\frac{1}{1+\delta}\frac{1}{1+r}(2+r)y,\,\,c_{1}^{*}=\frac{\delta}{1+\delta}(2+r)y
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
c_{0}^{*}>y\Leftrightarrow\frac{1}{1+r}>\delta,\,\,c_{1}^{*}>y\Leftrightarrow\frac{1}{1+r}<\delta
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Consider an equilibrium of 2 agents, with preferences given by:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
U_{A}=log(c_{0})+\delta log(c_{1}),\,\,U_{B}=log(d_{0})+\mu log(d_{1})
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
Equilibrium
\]

\end_inset

should be at 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 such that:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mu<\frac{1}{1+r}<\delta
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
And indeed:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
c_{0}^{*}-y=\frac{1}{1+\delta}\frac{2+r}{1+r}y-y
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
d_{o}^{*}-y=\frac{1}{1+\mu}\frac{2+r}{1+r}y-y
\]

\end_inset

Summing the above equations (the sum of the demands must be 0):
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
0=\left(\frac{1}{1+\delta}+\frac{1}{1+\mu}\right)\frac{2+r}{1+r}-2
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now it can be divided by 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{1}{2}\left(\frac{1}{1+\delta}+\frac{1}{1+\mu}\right)=\frac{1+r}{1+(1+r)}=\frac{1}{1+\frac{1}{1+r}}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Taking 2 individuals with the same income, we can find out that 
\series bold
the interest rate is between their time preferences
\series default
.
\end_layout

